text: an #edit inspired by artist, #zoebuckman’s project: “let her rave”. this particular work of buckman’s was a response to an excerpt from #johnkeats’ poem, “#odeonmelancholy”: “or if thy mistress some rich anger shows/ imprison her soft hand, and #letherrave/ and feed deep, deep upon her peerless eyes.” keats’ slightly misogynistic views struck a chord with buckman, who turned the aforementioned three-word phrase, pictured here, into a cry of #femaleempowerment in her #art pieces, designing boxing gloves made with wedding dress materials. look it up and see for yourself! her work is amazing & powerful. buckman is presenting a clear message here for all to see, but especially women who right now appear to be breaking free of such improsements; even if you are, or feel like your hands have been improsined, know that you are strong and you still have the power to fight back...rave✊🏾 @zoebuckman #womenpower #metoo #believesurvivors #womenstrong #womensrights #empowerment “#thispussygrabsback!” #timesup #womensmarch #edits #feminism #feminist #malefeminist #raveon #followme #followformore #followmeformore

text:
aly raisman
olympic gold medalist, gymnastics
hero
__
i grew up idolizing the women of usa gymnastics for their skill, poise, confidence, and superhuman abilities. little did i know, they were so much more than that. this year, aly raisman was one of the women who blew the lid off a decades long history of sexual abuse in the usa gymnasics community. after showing the world what she could do physically, she took the opportunity to make the world listen to what she had to say. along the way, she inspired a whole new generation of women to be strong, and speak out agains abuse and injustice. thank you, aly, for telling your gut-wrenching story. it matters. she, among others, stood up against a global institution, and burned it to the ground.
.
from #vanityfair: few icons of american girlhood are as symbolically complex as elite gymnasts. they appear on the mat as tiny shining birds: gems sewn into their leotards sparkling under bright competition lights, and colorful bows plopped on their french-braided hairdos like feathered crowns. scouts looking for young gymnasts with the potential to reach the olympics sometimes spot girls as young as seven. their careers usually peak before they can vote and end before they can legally order a glass of wine in a restaurant. yet they are athletes of extraordinary accomplishment and fortitude. they’re strong women, or girls becoming women, who fly through the air seemingly by sheer force of will. as a child glued to the television during the summer olympics in the 1980s, i thought of them as real-life versions of superwoman. women of steel, lighter than air.
.
in recent months, raisman has also assumed the role of captain in this fight. along with a small army of former olympians, including jamie dantzscher and jordyn wieber, she hopes that by speaking out about the factors that led to nassar’s abuse they will ultimately engineer a vast redesign of her sport’s culture. they are a new kind of american hero.
__

text:
#미투(me too)는 요새 확산 되고 있다. 
갑자기 #미투(me too ) 라는 단어를 왜 꺼내냐 “ 나도 당했다 “ 라는 글을 올리고 싶어서 이기 때문이다. 이 글을 보는 사람들은 피해자가 이상하다거나 가해자가 이상한 이유로 분명 갈릴 것이다. 이유를 감당하고 난 이 글을 감당하고 올린다. 
난 미투(me too) 라는 것을 이번에 알게되었다. 이번에 알게 된 계기로 여태껏 당해온 것을 한 개씩 올려볼까 한다.
동호회와 모임을 하다 보면 사람을 많이 알게되지만, 그건 누구나 알고 나오는 것이라 생각 한다 . 하지만 남자의 욕망은 남자 본인이 감당해야 한다고 생각한다. 외롭다 하여 여자를 성폭행 또한 성추행 한다는 것은 절대적으로 용서 할 수 없다. 본인의 집으로 가자 하여 커피 마시며 이야기 하자며 여자를 꼬득이며 본인이 손이 점점 여자의 가슴으로 올라가기 시작하고 여자가 막을라고 하고 나갈라 하여도 남자는 온 힘으로 다른 곳을 만지기 시작한다. 
도저히 용납할 수 없으며 납득할 수 없다. 콩밥을 먹어도 콩밥을 먹고 나온다고 하여도 이 부분은 남자들이 뉘우치고 다시 꺠닫고 해야 하는 부분이다.

text:
grateful that i've had the privilege to share about my idea on @tedxunivindowomen about how we, as a community can actually prevent sexual violence.
as much as i admire the #metoo movement, i feel that it shouldn't be a burden for the victims alone to speak up. we, as part of the society, needs to own up to our responsibility as an active bystander and shows that we're on their side. 
change is more than legislative and organizational policy reform; it's also about the actual day-to-day practice. pay attention to what you are doing to hold yourself and others accountable, and respond if you see or hear about an incident of sexual harassment or abuse. it is time for us to do our part to stop sexual violence.

text:
9)@courtneymelba - ‘nameless, faceless’⁣
one of the positives to come from the #metoo era has been the kick-ass soundtrack, and though this tragicomic anthem was written before the movement, it most definitely captures the temperature of the times. courtney turns her celebrated talent for witty observation towards gallows humour, but the charming melodies and bouncing, fuzzy guitars barely soften the bite of her words or the violence she’s addressing.⁣
⁣
‘i wanna walk through the park in the dark/men are scared that women will laugh at them’, she sings in the chorus, paraphrasing margaret atwood in a potent lyrical backflip; ‘women are scared that men will kill them.’ coupled with the all-too-relatable image of her keys balled in her fists in self-defence, it’s a devastating portrait of the fear that women commonly experience in what should be the safest of spaces. ⁣
⁣
‘nameless, faceless’ is as much an amped-up riposte to toxic online culture as it is misogyny, and while the song doesn’t strictly propose that one always escalates to the other, it shows the two aren’t mutually exclusive either. courtney should know. despite the global adoration behind her debut album, there’s been a nasty undercurrent of hostility mixed in with the tidal wave of praise. ⁣
the internet cynics who’ve barraged the 30yo songwriter with a torrent of negativity and blatantly non-musical insults, are (let’s be real) typically dudes. the unwarranted sexism is exhausting, but courtney transforms it into something empowering. she doesn’t play the victim, she flips the tables, giving those same anonymous online critics a starring role in ‘nameless, faceless’, undressing their pent-up anger as a symptom of loneliness, frustration, and fragile male ego. she feeds the trolls with kindness, offering her sympathies and even a hug: ‘i’m real sorry/’bout whatever happened to you’. ⁣
⁣
that she wraps all those sentiments and social analysis into a catchy, deadpan indie rock single only proves how accomplished a songwriter courtney barnett has become. breaking the golden rule of the internet - ‘don’t read the comments!’ - didn’t hurt her, it only made her stronger.⁣
#musicaladventcalendar🎶🎅🏻

text:
one of my favourite quotes from lao tzu and so very true. everyone has their own journey and challenges along the way. many of us know where we want to go but our conditioning tells us that it's too hard, or too far away, but if you start placing one foot in front of the other , and taking it one it one step, one breath, one day at a time you will eventually get to where you want to go. i never thought in a million years i'd be where i am today, for so long i was stuck being strangled by my past, the trauma, the pain and i thought i would never be able to get out of it, but here i am today living, loving a life of happiness. i am growing each day, and still taking it one step at a time.
🦄❤️🧡💛💚💙💜🤸‍♀️🚗🧘‍♀️👩‍👧🌈🧗‍♀️👣🕉️

text:
started writing down little victories in this ptsd journal. i'm not always good at journaling consistently. i often do it for a few months, stop, feel like i have to rip out stuff i've written and start over again.

but this time i'm making a conscious effort to not feel like i have to rip up what i've written. i'll be working with my therapist, really digging deep and working on figuring out why i feel like that. perhaps it's because of everything i've been through, the desire for a clean slate i'll never get in real life. the one i've always wanted, and the chance to start over with friendships that i ruined by being too consumed with anger and frustration about what happened to me.

what are you guys journaling about? what do you guys do to fight ptsd?

#ptsd #mentalhealthawareness #sexualabuse #journaling #metoo #selfcare

text:
are you afraid of starting a business, a movement, or sharing your own thoughts with the world because you’re afraid of what other people will think?
.
#metoo!
.
but not anymore. this is who i’m meant to be, this is what i’m passionate about, and i whole heartedly believe my purpose in life is to share what i love with like-minded individuals.
.
lately, i’ve noticed a lot of my old peers taking a step towards doing whatever it is they have been yearning to do in life despite the fear they had jumping into it in the beginning, and they’re crushing it!
.
so, i thought to myself, why aren’t you doing the same? why are you afraid still? if they can do it, why can’t i?
.
well, i can. the problem was just taking the leap and getting started.
.
can you relate to that? ever wanted to do something so bad, but you were already comfortable with where you were and accepted whatever it was that you believed so you just stayed put? well, let me tell you something, in order to grow, you must be uncomfortable!
.
so here i am, uncomfortable as hell, sharing what i love with all of you because i refuse to be afraid any longer.
.
i’m not sure why we have let society suppress us, for fear of not being liked, or being judged. no one has a right to judge who we are, much less voice their own opinion about what it is that makes us happy.
.
anyways, that’s my rant! i can’t wait to continue to share what fuels me with all of you in hopes that at least some of you can relate or will learn something from it. thank you to those who have showed their support by sharing my posts, liking my posts, and saying such kind, motivating things. it means so much!

text: the cover story in this week’s sunday styles section of the @nytimes is a story i worked on with @seligsonh about the recent proliferation of men’s groups such as the @themankindproject and @_evryman_ in context of the #metoo movement, male privilege and toxic masculinity. these groups take many forms, employ a variety of techniques and are taking place all across the country but the main objective seems to be to create a safe space for men to exhibit vulnerability, shame, fear, anger and helplessness in the empathetic company of other men. in the short time i spent with them i saw a remarkable amount of eye contact, authentic participation, attentive listening, explosive rage and uncontrollable sobbing. there may be some disagreement about the methods and models but one thing is clear: there are many men making earnest attempts to improve their emotional awareness and personal accountability. this can only be of benefit not only to them and the other men around them but to the women and children in their lives.

text:
g a s l i g h t i n g // is psychological abuse #advocate #idaho ——————————————————————
gaslighting is a type of abuse that leaves survivors questioning every memory they have.
they may hear things like “you’re overreacting, it wasn’t that bad,” “you’re just being emotional,” or “that never happened!”
any of these accusation alone could drive a person crazy, but when they’re part of a regular barrage of criticism aimed at controlling an individual, they’re more than rude — they’re abusive. 
swipe through to read about the things abusers do when they’re gaslighting. —————————————————————— #lifestyle #family #loveshouldnthurt #december #enddv #byui #dvfacts #dancing #entrepreneur #fall #design #wellness #marketing #friends #idaho #timesup #metoo #idaho #health #breakthesilence #idaho #graphicdesign #healthy #winter

any of these accusation alone could drive a person crazy, but when they’re part of a regular barrage of criticism aimed at controlling an individual, they’re more than rude — they’re abusive.

text:
well, how come you only want tomorrow?
with its promise of something hard to do
a real-life adventure
worth more than pieces of gold
blue skies above, sun on your arms
strength in your stride and hope
in those squeaky-clean eyes

you'll get chilly receptions
everywhere you go
blinded with desire
i guess the season is on

so you train by shadow boxing
search for the truth
but it's all, but it's all used up
break open your million-dollar weapon
and push your luck
still you push, still you push your luck
a broken-nosed mogul are you
one of the new-wave boys

same old thing in brand new drag
comes sweeping into view

as ugly as a teenage millionaire
pretending it's a whizz-kid world
you'll take me aside, and say

well, david, what shall i do?
they wait for me in the hallway
i'll say, don't ask me
i don't know any hallways
but they move in numbers
and they've got me in a corner
i feel like a group of one
no, no, they can't do this to me

i'm not some piece of teenage wildlife

those midwives to history
put on their bloody robes
and the word is that the hunted one
is out there on his own

and you're alone
for maybe the last time
and you breathe for a long time
then you howl like a wolf
in a trap and you daren't look behind

you fall to the ground
like a leaf from a tree
and look up one time
at that vast blue sky
scream out of line
as they shoot you down

no, no, i'm not a piece of teenage wildlife

i'm not a piece of teenage wildlife

and no one will have seen
and no one will confess
the fingerprints will prove
that you couldn't pass the test
there'll be others on the line
filing past, who'll whisper low
i miss you, he really had to go
well, each to his own
he was another piece of teenage wildlife

nother piece of teenage wildlife

nother piece of teenage wild

wild

wild

wild

david bowie

text:
well, how come you only want tomorrow?
with its promise of something hard to do
a real-life adventure
worth more than pieces of gold
blue skies above, sun on your arms
strength in your stride and hope
in those squeaky-clean eyes

you'll get chilly receptions
everywhere you go
blinded with desire
i guess the season is on

so you train by shadow boxing
search for the truth
but it's all, but it's all used up
break open your million-dollar weapon
and push your luck
still you push, still you push your luck
a broken-nosed mogul are you
one of the new-wave boys

same old thing in brand new drag
comes sweeping into view

as ugly as a teenage millionaire
pretending it's a whizz-kid world
you'll take me aside, and say

well, david, what shall i do?
they wait for me in the hallway
i'll say, don't ask me
i don't know any hallways
but they move in numbers
and they've got me in a corner
i feel like a group of one
no, no, they can't do this to me

i'm not some piece of teenage wildlife

those midwives to history
put on their bloody robes
and the word is that the hunted one
is out there on his own

and you're alone
for maybe the last time
and you breathe for a long time
then you howl like a wolf
in a trap and you daren't look behind

you fall to the ground
like a leaf from a tree
and look up one time
at that vast blue sky
scream out of line
as they shoot you down

no, no, i'm not a piece of teenage wildlife

i'm not a piece of teenage wildlife

and no one will have seen
and no one will confess
the fingerprints will prove
that you couldn't pass the test
there'll be others on the line
filing past, who'll whisper low
i miss you, he really had to go
well, each to his own
he was another piece of teenage wildlife

nother piece of teenage wildlife

nother piece of teenage wild

wild

wild

wild

david bowie

text: this shoot was epic, albeit a fail. 😂 my first attempt at a #wonderwoman photoshoot in nov 2017. too many distractions — over a dozen gals in the room, tequila, @champagnepapi drake blasting (love drake, my request), too little prop/ pose prep (all a hot mess). 😂🎉 so it was vetoed from the book’s final cut. lol. come over for some tequila one day - have a good laugh as i show you the rest. 🍹🙃 you’ve gotta know my childhood story and my namesake - the 80’s @wonderwomanfilm wonder woman @reallyndacarter - how i named myself lynda in front of the preschool (a little refugee girl at 3yrs old) to appreciate the effort. i’ll be trying it again in 2019! for now — download the kindle book to see what images did make it!! go to @freedomandfeminism (link in bio), our amazon page, or website and purchase our book. print copy - coming in the new year (dozens more images and bonuses)!! 20 women. 20 powerful stories. the call of freedom. a stunning book about a women’s journey towards freedom. with stories of trauma, grief, oppression, sexual empowerment, pleasure, motherhood, friendship, true love and triumph. you’ll be blown away by evocative and powerful photos (celebrating every woman’s right to expression)! #losangeles #newyork #ownit #wonderwoman #newyorkcity #nyc #lifecoach #leadershipcoaching #manhattan #grace #lovewins #leadership #freedom #freefem #freedomandfeminism #feminism #metoo #timesup  #heroine #shero #superhero @coachlyndanguyen

text:
it’s been a week of accelerated effort and commitments to end violence against women in all its forms. 
we participated at an interactive session on ending violence against women in elections. kudos to @unwomen @unwomen_africa @unwomennigeria on the launch of the programming guide on ending violence against women in elections (vawe). in pic: country rep, un women nigeria ms. comfort lamptey addressing the house. 
violence against women in elections is not just a violation of the civic rights of women to vote, be voted for, or participate in the electoral process at various levels, it is a denial of their rights to be part of a free, fair and inclusive democracy. these incidents must be addressed because women’s rights are primarily human rights. -

text:
i'm fortunate enough to never had the need to use the hashtag #metoo but don't let the fear of societal judgement be the reason another crime goes unreported.
.
sexual harrassment and assault is a criminal offence, irregardless of your sex or gender. no victim should have to feel ashamed to report a crime just because society finds any feasible excuse to justify such heinous acts. it's time to stop gender stereotyping and start thinking logically about this. doesn't hurt to have a little common sense, now does it?
.
#endgenderstereotypes #metoomovement #notapromo #justmythoughts

text:
it’s been a week of accelerated effort and commitments to end violence against women in all its forms. 
we participated at an interactive session on ending violence against women in elections. kudos to @unwomen @unwomen_africa @unwomennigeria on the launch of the programming guide on ending violence against women in elections (vawe). in pic: our founder @inimfonetuk facilitating the interactive discussion at the launch. 
violence against women in elections is not just a violation of the civic rights of women to vote, be voted for, or participate in the electoral process at various levels, it is a denial of their rights to be part of a free, fair and inclusive democracy. these incidents must be addressed because women’s rights are primarily human rights. -

text:
it’s been a week of accelerated effort and commitments to end violence against women in all its forms. 
we participated at an interactive session on ending violence against women in elections. kudos to @unwomen @unwomen_africa @unwomennigeria on the launch of the programming guide on ending violence against women in elections (vawe). in pic: nigeria country rep., un women, ms. comfort lamptey with our founder @inimfonetuk at the launch. 
violence against women in elections is not just a violation of the civic rights of women to vote, be voted for, or participate in the electoral process at various levels, it is a denial of their rights to be part of a free, fair and inclusive democracy. these incidents must be addressed because women’s rights are primarily human rights. -

text:
recently, i have been reasoning through the fear, obligation, and guilt i had during my relationship. before i understood what was happening, i felt a moral obligation to stay. he would quote scripture saying i had no biblical reason to divorce. i felt fearful when he told me no one else cared, he was the reason i had a car, a phone etc. i felt guilty when he tried to make me think i was just as bad as him or that i should be more forgiving. when i left for the last time, he used the usual tactics (fake apologies, gifts, proclaiming his love). once he realized i wasn’t coming back, he came after me with everything he had. he’s threatened to show family members texts where i complained about them out of anger or ignorance, he’s threatened to expose intimate photos of me from our marriage in court, he’s projecting his alcohol use onto me, requesting my medical records (since i took an antidepressant about three years ago), and he is smearing my name to make me sound unstable. it’s hard to comprehend how someone you thought you loved and could trust would intentionally hurt you and try to make you fearful. i have had a hard time forgiving myself for the mistakes i made, but understand that i was groomed and manipulated very easily. 
the best thing i have done for myself is to be 100% truthful. i have told my family everything i could have possibly said about them, i’ve exposed any drinking or smoking that occurred with this man, and i’ve been honest about the darkest details of the relationship. i am so grateful and undeserving of a family who stands by me through this storm. they know the mistakes i’ve made and it has only made us more faithful. i am not afraid to expose myself in the process of exposing him. if he shows others nude photos of me, that were meant for my husband, i will live. i know i am well and i am stable. i have made mistakes, but i am not a criminal and i am not abusive.✌🏻#narcissisticabuse #narcissisticpersonalitydisorder #psychopathfree #metoo #sociopath #npd #healingfromhiddenabuse #fearobligationguilt

text:
the recent #metoo movement in india has made one thing very clear: many victims of workplace sexual harassment are more comfortable posting about their experiences on social media than filing a formal complaint. among them are also ones that have resorted to social media only because they did not get justice through the law.

this is hardly surprising as the current sexual harassment law in india does offer perpetrators several loopholes to escape. moreover, even though many organisations are not fully compliant with the law, they are yet to be penalised.

be.artsy helps companies successfully prevent sexual harassment at the workplace with the support of the existing law and not by depending completely on it. for more information, write to: shipra@be-artsy.com. .

text:
it’s been a week of accelerated effort and commitments to end violence against women in all its forms. 
we participated at an interactive session on ending violence against women in elections. kudos to @unwomen @unwomen_africa @unwomennigeria on the launch of the programming guide on ending violence against women in elections (vawe). in pic: nigeria country rep. un women, ms. comfort lamptey with our founder @inimfonetuk (r) and our head of contacts mrs. tochi aguiyi-akujua @lynongod at the launch. 
violence against women in elections is not just a violation of the civic rights of women to vote, be voted for, or participate in the electoral process at various levels, it is a denial of their rights to be part of a free, fair and inclusive democracy. these incidents must be addressed because women’s rights are primarily human rights. -

day 15 | december 09 
because we have accepted to hide the abuse we suffer, because we have decided to be silent through the hurt. because we don’t speak loud enough or often enough. because of the fear, the tears and the stares. but no more! 
it is time to hear me too, it is our time to stand up and fight against any abuse or violation of any girl, woman or child. we will no longer sit still and be silent. 
we will honour ourselves by standing up and speaking as we take back our power.

the time is now. it is time for change!
.

text:
christmas party 🎄🎅🏻
.
nursery christmas party ✅
cheese and wine night ✅
one tired and emotional mummy✅
.
christmas is in full swing over here after a day packed full of the festive feels yesterday! and this one took it all in her stride with minimal moaning ❤️ and despite huge amounts of distraction and quite a blip in our toileting journey only 2 very small toileting accidents! #winning .
our day started with party prep followed by partying hard with friends, disco lights, father christmas and numerous crafts (very proud to say all the glitter you see in this picture is glitter left from previous years... none new bought this year and once its gone, its gone!) followed by a cheeky trip to the pub with our lovely nursery team finished off with a cheese and wine night with family ❤️ if that's not festive, i don't know what is!
.
of course, our day yesterday was bitter sweet..... a year ago we lost our baby, our much wanted, much loved baby and i spent my first night away from arabella while in hospital. needless to say i held her extra tight all day and night yesterday and i will continue to do so today as we remember our beautiful baby ewan ❤️

text:
dr shruti kapoor is an award-winning gender equality activist, economist, and social entrepreneur who is passionate about the safety of girls and women. shaken by the horrific gang rape in delhi 2012, she founded her organisation, sayfty, in june 2013 to educate and empower the women and girls of india against violence. the initiative aims at creating awareness of laws and legal rights around the issue of violence against women. it also uses digital media, tech-for-good, and storytelling to advocate for women’s safety. 
in 2016, the white house nominated dr kapoor as a change-maker for the united state of women summit 2016. sayfty was awarded the people’s choice award by femverstising (2015) and won a state recognition award by the uttar pradesh government in india for the organization’s work on safety and education of girls. 
dr kapoor holds a phd in economics from the university of california. she has consulted at un women and the world bank in washington dc. she has also served as an adjunct professor of economics at occidental college in los angeles. more recently, she served on the un inter-agency network on youth development working group on youth and gender equality task force and social media committees to inaugurate the united nations youth forum for the commission on the status of women. dr kapoor is also a regular contributor on gender issues and network member of apolitical, a global policy platform and a network of policymakers and thought leaders.

dr kapoor has addressed many national and international public forums including the youth assembly at the united nations, the world woman summit, the world urban forum, and merit 360. she is dedicated to using digital media to raise awareness and make our cities safer for women and girls. (words adapted from http://sayfty.com/about-our-founder/) image: adapted from sayfty.com

text:
today marked 70 years of the universal declaration of human rights, it proclaimed a historic universal norm that we are all born free and equal in dignity and rights. however, today, in many parts of the world,  even in my country, those who are different are still not treated with dignity and respect. their freedom is abused and they are considered as less of a human being.  refugees are viewed as "invaders", lgbti+ is called "disease", those profess to different interpretation of religion are categorized as infidels, indigenous people are marginalized and women are still imprisoned by patriarchy. persecution is assumed as heroic and discrimination is a part of "culture". many things have changed in 70 years,  but circumstances are nowhere near our vision.  it's time for us to speak up more!  i know that we have spoken up,  but it's not enough,  we must speak up louder and unite our voices! 
#standup4humanrights #udhr #freedom #equality #withrefugees #lovewins #minotivist #gerakbersama #hearmetoo #metoo #kitaagni #humanrights #amnestyinternational #humanrightswatch #freedomhouse #tedx #tedxtalk

text:
🌎it's a man's world!🌍
.
.
men's adventure magazines, the postwar pulps.

defines "over the top".
.
these magazines were considered the absolute bottom of the barrel when they were published. to be truthful, they're still offensive today. but now they can be examined in terms of sociology and popular culture. if you don't pass judgement on their content, you can marvel at the sheer audacity of these publishers! nothing was too outrageous to be published in these mags - they define the term "raw." this book has extremely high production values and fascinating commentary, whether you agree with it or not. wholesome entertainment? no. fascinating? yes! #itsamansworld #mansworld  #jordanbpeterson #leftwing #pulpfiction #pulp #book #trash #educateyourself #americanhistory #exploitation #metoo #metoomovement

text:
for those 87 million people probably wondering what was actually done with their data, i went back to christopher wylie, the ex-cambridge analytica employee who blew the whistle on the company’s problematic operations in the observer. according to wylie, all you need to know is a little bit about data science, a little bit about bored rich women, and a little bit about human psychology.

step one, he says, over the phone as he scrambles to catch a train: - when you’re building an algorithm, you first need to create a training set. that is: no matter what you want to use fancy data science to discover, you first need to gather the old-fashioned way. before you can use facebook likes to predict a person’s psychological profile, you need to get a few hundred thousand people to do a 120-question personality quiz.

the “training set” refers, then, to that data in its entirety: the facebook likes, the personality tests, and everything else you want to learn from. most important, it needs to contain your “feature set”: - the underlying data that you want to make predictions on, wylie says. - in this case, it’s facebook data, but it could be, for example, text, like natural language, or it could be clickstream data – the complete record of your browsing activity on the web. - those are all the features that you want to [use to] predict. at the other end, you need your target variables, the things that you’re trying to predict for. so in this case, personality traits or political orientation, or what have you.

alex hern
the guardian

for those 87 million people probably wondering what was actually done with their data, i went back to christopher wylie, the ex-cambridge analytica employee who blew the whistle on the company’s problematic operations in the observer. according to wylie, all you need to know is a little bit about data science, a little bit about bored rich women, and a little bit about human psychology.

step one, he says, over the phone as he scrambles to catch a train: - when you’re building an algorithm, you first need to create a training set. that is: no matter what you want to use fancy data science to discover, you first need to gather the old-fashioned way. before you can use facebook likes to predict a person’s psychological profile, you need to get a few hundred thousand people to do a 120-question personality quiz.

the “training set” refers, then, to that data in its entirety: the facebook likes, the personality tests, and everything else you want to learn from. most impoant, it needs to contain your “feature set”: - the underlying data that you want to make predictions on, wylie says. - in this case, it’s facebook data, but it could be, for example, text, like natural language, or it could be clickstream data – the complete record of your browsing activity on the web. - those are all the features that you want to [use to] predict. at the other end, you need your target variables, the things that you’re trying to predict for. so in this case, personality traits or political orientation, or what have you.

alex hern
the guardian

text: calluses. part 1. when i was 12 yrs old i started to burry feelings, some of them in unmarked graves. around that time i was going through so much turmoil and no parental protection, support or guidance. i developed trichotillomania, pulling hair out of my skin because the pain made me feel something. anything. i wasn’t much of the cutter, but i did walk around the school yard with few other lost boys carrying a disposable razor blade inside my mouth. flipping it in circles with my tongue and sliding it out like a snake looking for trouble. i was 13 then. by the time i was 16 i already had scars on my skin from cigarette burns. i no longer self-inflict pain however, i’m not removed from it whatsoever. for example, tattoos are therapeutic for me in the same manner the retreat is therapeutic to a deeply spiritual person. i sought attention in the form of love i wasn’t getting anymore and i’ve found it among those, whose souls resembled stained, wrinkled treasure maps with not enough clues and directions. i grew into desensitized man. very few things will affect me emotionally today. looking at the positive aspect of this, calluses can represent hard work, determination, dedication, purpose, persistence and growth. when i find myself pealing back leather skin at the top corner on the inside of my palms, i’m reminded to leave it alone. text:
calluses part 2. (continued from the previous post...) whatever feeling is buried in shallow ground will find it’s way out. i formed tough skin because it meant survival on the psychological and emotional level. everyone has past that can be dug up. no person is free of stains. we all have said and done things in our short lives that had left impact on others both indirectly and directly. but we all change. some for better and some for worse, but we all change. how i’m living today is lightyears away from who i was 5, 10, 15, 25 yrs ago. i’ve changed lifestyles, and careers, i’ve experimented with music, sex and drugs. i’ve hurt people and stole from some. i’ve gotten hurt by people and got robbed by some. i grew and i keep growing. i learned to allow myself to be coachable. people are judged by observation on who they are becoming, what are they building and how they’re contributing to society. they are also judged by their past. anyone is welcome to dig in between pages of my book. i invite you to read between the cursive lines. in these hypersensitive times and extreme lack of compassion and empathy, in the world so beautiful and promising, we are all sinners. i’m neither overly sensitive, nor do i seek comfort in pain. to play with me you will need to be ok with looking in your own reflection of the water that stands still. you will have to be happy with your own reflection should you choose to skip rocks.

(continued from the previous post...) whatever feeling is buried in shallow ground will find it’s way out. i formed tough skin because it meant survival on the psychological and emotional level. everyone has past that can be dug up. no person is free of stains. we all have said and done things in our short lives that had left impact on others both indirectly and directly. but we all change. some for better and some for worse, but we all change. how i’m living today is lightyears away from who i was 5, 10, 15, 25 yrs ago. i’ve changed lifestyles, and careers, i’ve experimented with music, sex and drugs. i’ve hurt people and stole from some. i’ve gotten hurt by people and got robbed by some. i grew and i keep growing. i learned to allow myself to be coachable. people are judged by observation on who they are becoming, what are they building and how they’re contributing to society. they are also judged by their past. anyone is welcome to dig in between pages of my book. i invite you to read between the cursive lines. in these hypersensitive times and extreme lack of compassion and empathy, in the world so beautiful and promising, we are all sinners. i’m neither overly sensitive, nor do i seek comfort in pain. to play with me you will need to be ok with looking in your own reflection of the water that stands still. you will have to be happy with your own reflection should you choose to skip rocks.

text:
through the mythological story of ahalya, this narrative’s attempt is to recite the ancient wisdom that helps build the much-needed inner strength to handle difficult situations. this work includes disclosures from indian puranas on the topic of woman’s bondage to a man. it also includes the narratives pertaining to ‘brahma rahasiya’ (the eternal secret) as declared in the ancient spiritual texts. 
the spark for this speculative fiction stems from a question – ‘did something similar to this #metoo issue occur during the days of ramayana and mahabharatha?’ this piece of work was developed by identifying the gaps in ahalya’s narrative in bala khanda of valmiki ramayana and attempting to fill it with the tales cryptically provided in uttara khanda. in addition to ramayana, various other ancient indian literature like mahabharata, panchatantra, jataka tales, lotus sutra, devi bhagvatam, and shiva purana were used in imagining and developing this narrative. 
the well-known sanskrit hymn that defines the panchakanys runs:
sanskrit transliteration
ahalyā draupadī kunti tārā mandodarī tathā ।
pañcakanyāḥ smarennityaṃ mahāpātakanāśinīḥ ॥ 
please do pick up your copy in

https://www.amazon.in/dp/b07l5sx2bb (india)

https://www.amazon.com/dp/b07l5sx2bb (global) 
#byme #metoo #supportindieauthors #mythology #ahalya #metoomovement #indianauthor

text:
i find that after past traumas surface, it takes several days for me to recalibrate my emotions. my sensitivity is heightened. i start looking for meaning in things that i didn't look for before.
.
i took this photo flying somewhere over the pacific ocean. after everything that happened this past week, i looked at this photo and started crying. i've traveled to so many places all over the earth since i reported that sexual assault in early 2014 and the whole time i believed i'd never get justice. but i was resilient enough to become a world traveler, a business owner, and an outspoken activist anyway.
.
i guess i realized that i didn't need justice from my trauma to rise above it.
-
#worldtraveler #travel #pacific #sunrise #sky #sexualassaultsurvivor #metoo #lifestyle #influencer #bossbabe #writer #activist #feminist #humanist

text:
hello, there. 👋🏼 welcome all you new followers. all together there’s over 20k of you now and that’s crazy to me. thank you for following and investing in my journey, whether that started today or reaches back to my childhood days. it’s been a crazy ride, that’s for sure.
.
.
i am a musician, a singer, and performer. i am a crafter, a traveler and a writer. i am a survivor of sexual abuse and a student of lifelong recovery. i am a wife, and a daughter and a sister. i am an avid reader, aspiring cook and i’m curious about just about anything. right now in my life, you can see a few glimpses of me by tuning in to the cma country christmas show tomorrow at 8/7 central on abc. you can read about my personal survivor story on my website and blog. you can check out the end of my special holiday shop sale where i’m selling a few of my handmade leatherworks. but i also invite you to keep adventuring along with me here on instagram. who knows where we’ll go but i’m so glad to have you along.
.
.
i’d love to know when you first started following along in my story...through my family’s band? saw some of mr. bootstraps photos? reality tv appearance? bought some leather bracelets? leave a comment and let me know!
👇🏻👇🏻👇🏻👇🏻👇🏻
.
.
. 📷 @mr.bootstraps #cmacountrychristmas #abctv #cma #countrychristmas #feelfreefeed #exploretocreate #metoo #greatsmokymountains #nationalpark #20k #bloggerlife #madeintn #nashvilleartist #singersongwriter #christmasgift #leatherwork #handmadegift #stayandwander #outdoorsy #liveoutdoors #adventureanywhere #folkcreative #smokies

i am a musician, a singer, and performer. i am a crafter, a traveler and a writer. i am a survivor of sexual abuse and a student of lifelong recovery. i am a wife, and a daughter and a sister. i am an avid reader, aspiring cook and i’m curious about just about anything. right now in my life, you can see a few glimpses of me by tuning in to the cma country christmas show tomorrow at 8/7 central on abc. you can read about my personal survivor story on my website and blog. you can check out the end of my special holiday shop sale where i’m selling a few of my handmade leatherworks. but i also invite you to keep adventuring along with me here on instagram. who knows where we’ll go but i’m so glad to have you along.
.
.
i’d love to know when you first staed following along in my story...through my family’s band? saw some of mr. bootstraps photos? reality tv appearance? bought some leather bracelets? leave a comment and let me know!
👇🏻👇🏻👇🏻👇🏻👇🏻
.
.
. 📷

hari: senin, 10 desember 2018
jam: registrasi dibuka pukul 16.00 wita
venue: cushcush gallery, jalan teuku umar gg. rajawali 1a, denpasar

festival ini gratis dan jangan lupa membawa tumbler/botol sendiri, karena acara ini berkomitmen zerowaste.

sampai jumpa di closing night #enambelasffestbali!

text:
in 2000 i marched for the first time. i was a freshman in college and excited to be newly elected to the schools lgbt organization. when we got to dc, we were met with signs like these. but also the standard ‘god hates fags’ sort. it was ok though because for the first time ever, i was surrounded by hundreds of thousands of gay people. the great aloneness i had felt all my life dissipated a little over those days. ♥️ those steps forward we’re followed by so many back. i marched backwards through darkness and in the company of unchecked sorrow. i was gay bashed, physically threatened and terrified. i heard lie after lie about my corrupt and abominable soul, and gods hatred of me. worse, i often hated myself. i tried to escape through drugs and unhealthy sex and various forms of self destruction. i was an apologist for the family and communities that made me feel so small. it was only when death was finally on my doorstep that i realized i had to take my power back from the assholes who would rather i just die. ♥️ i want the transgendered, the gay ones still forced into closets, the triple whammy black lesbians, the gender non conforming children, the queer of all shapes, sizes, colors and types to see their beauty. i want them to see the history behind our movement. i want them to know that the shame society tries to put on us is just a defense mechanism of those in power. if god is real, she made no mistake in your lovely souls, she gifted you this body as canvas for expression, a space to make real your hearts truth. the shape and policing of your genitals is not a godly concern. never trust someone who tells you other wise. love on siblings! •
•
•

•

text:
saturday nights, we 
open a bottle of scotch 
and sit in our balconies
a common wall and 
a bucket of ice in between

confessions start flowing

you tell me about 
the men you married –
lawyer, excessive drinker, passionate lover
strictly in that order

my count is three as well, i say, 
making up two girls beside my ex-wife

needlessly, we then get explicit
priding on promiscuous behaviour

elevators, construction sites, 
cliffs, mountains, beaches, 
everything finds a mention

and soon, we are atop the common wall, 
fumbling and then tumbling over, 
a few sorrys landing between the kisses

our saturday nights never have a closure
but on sundays, we try our best
as we argue about our partners

i disapprove of the way 
you speak about your men, 
you, of how i don’t

you roll your eyes
at how forgetful i am
and i, at how forgiving you are

midway, we stop with the words, 
quieten down and look away
taking the time 
to roll back to our realities

we can’t be a couple, 
we remind each other
as our naked bodies pull away
slowly, reluctantly 
with a voice that breaks as it speaks

but we persist
we cannot be a couple
not the one we should not be.
.
.
animesh ganguly.
(@penningdownthemind)
.
.
.

man blir verkligen fysiskt illamående av hur en liten klick har kunnat blunda för övergrepp under så lång tid.

text:
"who makes you different from another....and what do you have that you did not receive?" (1 cor. 4:7) 
lavish on these truths this snowy sunday!

1) god has gifted each believer at least one gift. (1 cor. 12:7)

2) the holy spirit determines who receives which gift. (1 cor. 12:11)

3) each gift is equally valuable. (1 cor. 12-26)

4) we are to use our gifts to serve others for the benefit of the body (rom.12:6-8; eph.4:12)

5) we are commanded to use our gifts. (1 peter 4:10) 
6) exercising our gifts will help us develop spiritual maturity (eph. 4:13). unsure where to start? 
lifeway provides "spiritual gifts assessment tools" online that will give you great clarification. happy discovering😁

text:
how many of you have been victims of harassment in any form? i think 90% of women have been through such traumatic experiences. they choose not to talk about these incidents because they are sure that no one will believe them. whenever they come forward with their stories, no one believes them and asks for proof of harassment. how can we provide proof? i was groped twice on the road while i was coming back from university. now if someone asks me for  proof, i won’t have it unless there are cameras installed in every location. whenever i think about these incidents, they haunt me. i am afraid to walk on the road alone. why is that? because we are not safe in this society. hear women when they tell you that they have been abused. hear them when they share their story with you. help them! try to protect them.  for how long will we be considered weak just because we are perceived as physically so? we may be physically weak but we aren’t weak emotionally. we are stronger than anyone and i believe that women need encouragement and if given that, you’ll see them conquering the world. we are strong and we need to be heard now. #timesup. we will shine. we will rise 💖
.
.
.
.
.
#hearmetoo @unwomenpakistan .
.
.
#women #harassment #metoo #sexualharassment #violence

text:
what can we do? •	tell people that violence against women and girls is never ok. •	if you suspect that a woman close to you is being abused, listen to and support her. tell her there are people who want to help. 
howe sound womens centre crisis line: 1-877-890-5711 •	believe women when they tell you they’ve been raped or abused. don’t ask about their behaviour and what they were wearing. listen to what they say without judging them. women never ask for nor deserve to be raped or abused. •	learn about violence against women and girls and what causes it. your education is a tool to end it. •	remember that silence is affirming. when we choose not to speak out about violence against women (or any other injustice) we are supporting it •	encourage and support those people in your community working to end all forms of violence against women and girls. •	talk to family and community members about how violence and fear of violence affect the daily lives of women and girls. talk about how you can support each other to help end violence. •	make your home violence-free. children who have witnessed or suffered from gender-based violence are more likely to become victims and abusers later in life. •	raise your sons and daughters to be equal and teach them that there is nothing that boys can do that girls cannot. •	volunteer to work with violence against women and girls prevention programs in your community. •	share decision-making with women in your life. discuss things with your partner and respect your partner’s opinions. •	if you are angry, count to 10 before reacting to something you hear or see. •	if a brother, friend, colleague, classmate or teammate is disrespectful to or is abusing a woman or a girl, do not look the other way — instead, find a way to talk about it with them. •	words are very powerful, especially when spoken by people with power over others. don’t use disrespectful words. 
#endvawg #vawg #16daysofactivism #howesoundwomenscentre #hearmetoo #metoo #16days

text:
“there were two seminal moments for me, which pierced through the mental notes i was making as i listened. one was hearing the insightful and generally brilliant esther perel expounding on how even now in the 21st century, gender roles require redefinition. she neatly dovetailed this assertion with the #metoo movement encompassing social justice for women, as well as opposition to sexual harassment in her discourse; male currency has intrinsically remained unchanged; women’s has changed ....sort of. well not enough anyway. the rules have changed, boundaries have shifted, but our modes of behaviour haven’t. basically, we’re in a bit of a pickle.”

hey friends, 
this case has been making it's rounds for 3 years. there have been celebrities, hardcore lawyers and documentaries discussing this case. 
read about cyntoia brown's story, watch the documentary, me facing life: cyntoia's story. just fyi: it is infuriating and painful to learn this story. make sure you have support and aren't struggling emotionally when you watch it.

@regran_ed from @sista_sexologist -  call to action---

*

text:
if you're offended by "baby it's cold outside" you're going to have a tough go of it in life. and so are your kids.
•first, you are completely ignoring the fact that the song is 74 years old--when women were ladies and men were gentlemen.
•her "protest" was typical of a way a lady would speak to a man instead of just downing some drinks and hopping into bed with him.
no one seems offended by those kinda lyrics when you hear them on the radio all year long.
men actually had to court women back in those days, a subtle dance that for both men and women no longer exists. sad but true.
•secondly, "what's in this drink?" does not imply that she was roofied, or at least it didn't in 1944. you don't need to be a historian to piece that puzzle together.
•she's sarcastically blaming her indecision on her drink, which again, came with the times. is that not obvious? •should we stop watching the wizard of oz because when they fall asleep in the poppy fields that means dorothy is on heroin? •moreover, what are you worried is going to happen?? that people will hear this song, completely misinterpret the lyrics (as you obviously have) and then decide to go date rape someone?
•i'd like to see the #metoo movement taken seriously. uproar over a holiday song, which clearly was not about abuse, has the opposite effect.
•if you were sexually abused, my heart goes out to you, but aren't we surrounded my far more obvious and offensive material on a daily basis that should be drawing the attention? is this really the right battle to fight?
•or maybe you're worried about your children and what they will think when they hear it? gee, maybe it's the perfect teachable moment to actually sit down and have a conversation with your child about how men and women used to be. most notably, not offended by every little thing that crossed their path. •yes, i agree, rudolph gets bullied in the animated version of "rudolph the red nosed reindeer." aaaaaaand?? wasn't that the point of the whole dang story!!??
•it's the ultimate story of redemption and turning the other cheek and doing what you gotta do in the face of adversity.
**continued ⬇️⬇️

text: ahead of every successful man is a woman. that's what i've always believed in. our country and indeed the world we live in consists of so many unsung and under-celebrated brave soldiers, i.e., women. at this women in law seminar, i was able to voice my beliefs regarding the kind of world we could be living in if insecure people stopped creating barriers for women so as to exclude them from shining in their respective fields and areas of talent. there are times when i speak out of anger or out of emotions or after a lot of thinking but here, what i've said comes straight from the heart. victims of sexual harassment find the legal system unwelcoming since those adjudicating upon their sense of violation question back as to what 'type of woman' she was. a bright, young girl gets stabbed 23 times and the defense counsel is only interested in her [quite normal and upright] past 'behaviour'? time to stop excluding women from the legal profession so that there is a turn in the tide of this prevailing injustice. a society which excludes its women can never succeed. a world which excludes women can never progress. #feminism #metoo #protection #inclusivity #black #women #muneebqadir #gender #rights #law #legal #timesup #pakistan

text: book 31 of 2018: i’d heard so much about this book but hesitated because i adored “a complicated kindness” but found “irma voth” so boring. but the library here had this so i thought i’d give it a whirl. it’s a short read (200 pages) but i didn’t exactly fly through it. it’s really brilliant and really powerful but the form of a book made entirely of meeting minutes got a bit tiresome at times, especially with so many names to keep up with. but i think it’s an incredibly important book and would totally recommend it unless you can’t deal with mentions of sexual violence. i’m really glad i read this after all. 📚

text:
this is how russians travel from earth to saturn !!! through dimensional portals... in 2015 nasa researchers disclosed the truth about time travel and dimensional portals. there are places all over the universe we can travel to in an instant, using energetic portals in space, and the use of our consciousness.
the proof is indeed mounting that there are portals to other worlds. though the documentation is still ‘sketchy’! apparently, tesla too was obsessed with time travel. he worked on a time machine and reportedly succeeded, saying: ‘i could see the past, present and future all at the same time.’ tesla’s time travel experiment: i could see the past, present and future all at the same time’

tesla had claimed to have invented a powerful particle-beam weapon, known as the “death ray,” that could have proved invaluable in the ongoing conflict. so rather than risk tesla’s technology falling into the hands of america’s enemies, the government swooped in and took possession of all the property and documents from his room at the new yorker hotel.
what happened to tesla’s files from there, as well as what exactly was in those files, remains shrouded in mystery—and ripe for conspiracy theories. the fbi has finally declassified its files on nikola tesla, but questions remain.

after nikola tesla was found dead in january 1943 in his hotel room in new york city, representatives of the u.s. government’s office of alien property seized many documents relating to the brilliant and prolific 86-year-old inventor’s work.

technology (mit) was tasked with evaluating his papers to determine whether they contained “any ideas of significant value.” according to the declassified files,🔥dr. john g. trump🔥reported that his analysis showed tesla’s efforts to be “primarily of a speculative, philosophical and promotional character” and said the papers did “not include new sound, workable principles or methods for realizing such results.

text: “i’m very pleased and proud to loan a piece of my artwork to @ymcanorfolk stepping stones cafe in norwich today. art has provided me a way in which to tackle some very difficult and dark moments in my life. and i hope that people visiting stepping stones can look at my work and find a glimmer of hope in whatever struggles they may be facing themselves. for me, it’s never been about just selling paintings. but about providing hope to those who feel lost and alone. after 14 years i’ve finally found my ‘voice’. i hope everyone visiting and working at stepping stones finds theirs.” - jamie. #art #artist #abstract #abstractart #creative #visualarts #norfolk #norwich #ymca #ymcanorfolk #charity #depression #mentalhealth #metoo #norfolkart #norfolkartist #raw #energy #emotionalcontent #artoninstagram #artchangesthings #thinkdifferent #paint #acrylic #canvas #artiststakerisks

text:
if we didn't already love @michelleobama enough - she only goes and admits that 'she' suffers from #impostersyndrome 😳

mrs obama spoke to an audience of 300 students at elizabeth garrett anderson school, islington as part of her worldwide book tour.

she first visited the school nine years ago, when she had only been first lady for a few months. asked how she felt to be seen as a "symbol of hope", mrs obama told the students: "i still have a little (bit of) impostor syndrome, it never goes away, that you're actually listening to me.
"it doesn't go away, that feeling that you shouldn't take me that seriously. what do i know? i share that with you because we all have doubts in our abilities, about our power and what that power is." michelle's honesty has sparked a raft of #metoo responses - although this really doesn't surprise us😢. everyday (sadly) we here so many stories from the mums on our courses about how they have not felt good enough / capable enough or even strong enough . we believe our unique real learning training has given lots of them self belief and the determination to succeed (although we always know you super mums have got it in you - we just help unlock it!). what about you? when have you experienced imposter syndrome and if you managed it - how have you overcome it? or do you have any tips of what we can do when we have moments of self doubt? we'd love to hear from you below 👇 and if you need some support then please do join our empowering women's fb group as we have lots of coaches andfb lives to tackle this very subject as we know how crippling it can be - hit the link in the bio to sign up 🔝
.
.
.
.
.
#empoweringwomenwithworkthatworks #empoweringwomen #workthatworks #impostersyndrome #whatisholdingyouback #confidence #empowering #empowerment #womensupportingwomen #mumssupportingmums #careers #careerbreak #maternityleave #facebookgroup#instamums #instamamas

text:
• medicalization of childbirth – a case of the stockholm syndrome.
•
increasingly, over-intervention in childbirth is depriving many women of autonomy, strength and even of their physical and mental health.
•
in spite of this well-documented fact, many doctors, midwives, women and ... sadly ... even many feminists confuse the injuries resulting from labor interventions with the dangerous “nature” of birth itself to the extent that the two are almost completely interwoven in the patriarchal narrative that defines childbirth.
•
with such a pervasive and internalized narrative of the female body’s fallibility and morbidity, no wonder lay-women can no longer tell what’s what.
•
most find a defeat by childbirth very likely – and when this defeat occurs you, of course, want to be in a place where you can be rescued...by labor interventions!
•
but what was it that actually caused the child “to almost die”? •  or the woman herself “to nearly die from postpartum hemorrhage”?
•  or other such stories created to boost confidence?
•
...not confidence in the woman’s ability to birth, that is, but rather to boost confidence in her rescue by the very labor interventions that in many cases almost kill her or her baby.
•
as long as the “dangerous, sickly, female body” appears scarier to us than the vast number of serious injuries caused by labor interventions, patriarchy’s medicalized imprisonment will falsely appear safer to childbearing women.
•
and that, ladies (and gentle men) is the very definition of the stockholm syndrome! •  #sverigeskvinnolobby  #enough #kvinfo  #hric  #informedconsent #birthtrauma  #patriarchy #misogyny #internalizedmisogyny  #obstetricviolence #birthactivism #feminism #feminist #metoo #improvingbirth #empoweredbirth #enough #metoobirth

text:
this weekend i started a new tradition with one of my absolute best friends, @kaitlync123, by my side.

each year, the anniversary of my assault is hard. if i’m being honest, most years i barely even make it out of bed.
but this year, i vowed to validate my progress rather than dwell on the pieces of myself i’m still missing.

so i got outside. i honored my body in the best way i know how. i celebrated what a resilient act of self-love my survival has been.

and i really just wanted to come back to my little sliver of the internet to say thank you for all of your kind words and support this weekend. i’m truly speechless over how well-received my storytelling on survival has been on this platform. thank you for trusting me with your experiences of survival, for believing in me, and mostly, for granting me a positive space to continue my healing.

if you’re reading this as a survivor of sexual assault, please know:
there is no shame in how you tell or don’t tell your story. there is no shame in taking a long time to tell your story. there is no shame in not posting about it publicly. there is no shame in creating boundaries about the details of your assault.

i know how it feels to be shamed for not speaking up, or for not speaking up sooner.
i know that the shame is part of our cycle of victim blaming.

i promise you, there’s nothing to be ashamed about.
you don’t owe anyone your story, or your advocacy, or your #metoo

if you’re reading as a survivor, please know:
i share my stories of survival for you, but i also share them for me.
my storytelling is part of my reclamation.
it is part of my demanding to be heard, when i was silenced for so long. it is how i take my power back. it is one of my loudest statements of self-love. storytelling has become an integral part of my recovery.
that doesn’t meant it’s part of yours— 
please remember, healing looks different on everyone.

if you’re reading this as a survivor, please know:
i see you.
i believe you.
i stand in solidarity with you.

text:
warning: sexual assault/harassment/rape

when i was 10 years old a family friend touched and abused me. he would start to reach his hands on to me and the more i would back away the closer he would get this went on for the next two years as well. when i was 12 my parents were all watching a movie and his father let him into my room saying his son was bored. he raped me. once he began i had no choice i was just frozen and trapped inside of myself after this i felt horrible. i would no longer eat or talk. i would just lay in bed and cry all day, even missing school. i attempted to kill myself just because he made me feel so absolutely worthless. my parents found me and put me with a therapist who helped me become a strong person again. i may not still have the innocence i did before but i am definitely stronger. i’m not completely better and i don’t think i ever will be, but i’ve learned that what happened didn’t make me worthless. 
#metoo #metoomovement #nomore

text:
he leído en el periódico que chile se debate entre la idea de rebautizar el aeropuerto de santiago con el nombre de pablo neruda. aquellas hermanas chilenas que tan duramente velan por los derechos de la mujer al otro lado del charco se han negado: se tacha a neruda de maltratador. ¿cómo iban a concederle tal homenaje? hay quienes defienden este plan ya que, como dijera garcía márquez en vida, neruda es «el más grande poeta del siglo xx». pero sus hazañas personales no le preceden de tan buena fama: acusado de abandonar a una hija enferma y de relatar en una de sus obras (póstumas) una violación. sinceramente, cuando llegué a esta parte de la noticia me quedé sin aliento. dicha obra se titula «confieso que he vivido» que recoge cómo, sirviéndose de su cargo diplomático, forzó a una muchacha que primero lo ignoró y luego llevó a su habitación para tener un encuentro «como el de un hombre y una estatua. ella mantuvo los ojos bien abiertos todo el tiempo, completamente inconsciente». y, sinceramente, llegados a este punto, no quise leer más. quienes critican esta decisión abogan por el nombre de gabriela mistral para renombrar dicho aeropuerto. sin embargo, los impulsores del proyecto defienden que lo que se pretende es «homenajear su obra», nada más.
.
he de decir que no conocía esta faceta del poeta, apenas he leído algunos de sus poemas en mi vida (de hecho, la foto es de uno procedente de «los versos del capitán» editado por @australeditorial).
.
el caso es que la noticia me ha hecho preguntarme si el legado artístico de un autor está condicionado por su vida personal, si es justo que su obra (o los homenajes que pueda recibir por ella) se vea corrompida por sus acciones.
¿vosotrxs qué pensais? ¿alguna vez habéis dejado de leer a alguien por datos biográficos como estos?
🔸
🔹
🔸
🔹

text:
tw: rape
maya was raped by an acquaintance a few weeks into her freshman year of college. as is the case for many survivors, maya didn’t immediately identify herself as a victim of sexual violence. she began processing her experience of sexual assault about six months later when she told a friend about what happened. “i was describing what happened to me, but i hadn’t put a word to it yet. the person i was talking to said, ‘he raped you.’ that’s when i first started processing it—when someone else called it out to me and made it more real. it was a big shift in how i had been processing my experience and it became a little easier for me to talk about. i used to try to tone it down for myself, to say i was ‘taken advantage of.’ but now it’s been really important for me to call it what it was—to use the word rape.” donate to rainn: fundraise.rainn.org/25sweaterss
#25daysofsweaters #metoo

text:
i’ve spent the last two saturday’s celebrating the life of my dear friend aisha millicent fraser who lost her life on november 17th in senseless and brutal act of domestic violence.

it’s taken me some time to make sense of this tragedy and while i’m still in disbelief, i have come to accept what has happened and move on to honor her name and legacy. aisha was such a humble person, it was not until reading her obituary and hearing people speak that i found out all that she had done in her 45 years on this earth. she gave so much to her students, served her community, exposed her daughters to so many wonderful experiences, was a loving daughter and had many amazing experiences of her own. 
one of the many wonderful things that a family member shared about aisha was that she finished everything that she started. this is how she has inspired me immediately. as a person who starts many things but only finishes ‘some’ i have made a promise to myself to honor aisha by finishing every project that i start moving forward. this is just one of the many ways that my life will become better from the legacy of aisha millicent fraser. she will truly be missed. 
#sayhername
#aishamfraser
#enough
#rememberingaisha
name: Jana Stewart

one of the many wonderful things that a family member shared about aisha was that she finished everything that she started. this is how she has inspired me immediately. as a person who starts many things but only finishes ‘some’ i have made a promise to myself to honor aisha by finishing every project that i start moving forward. this is just one of the many ways that my life will become better from the legacy of aisha millicent fraser. she will truly be missed. 
#sayhername
#aishamfraser
#enough
#rememberingaisha

text:
submission from a man addressing other men on the issue of consent/violence: i was in a relationship with a woman who had opened up to me about her sexual assault. he was good friends with the both of us. someone you would never think would do something like this. my first instinct was feeling an overwhelming amount of anger. i wanted something to be done about this. she told me she did not want this to be reported over fear that everyone in our school would find out. it was incredibly hard to constantly have to be around him in school and not being able to say or do anything. it took some time, but i eventually turned that anger into passion. i began teaching courses to multiple high school districts about consent and personal boundaries geared towards young men. it created a conversation about topics these young men have never discussed or thought about. this opened my eyes up to the unfortunate reality all women face and how little these men knew about the issue. i have never met a woman who does not have a story. i'm not perfect and i have made my fair share of mistakes regarding this issues. respect her choice on the matter period, do not make this about yourself. it is her story to tell, not yours. never, under any circumstance, force her to open up about her experience if she is not ready. do not perpetuate the cycle of violence by going after the person, it is not justice by any means. finally, heal. this is not a glamorous journey by any means, but your feelings in this situation matter and they need to be discussed and acknowledged. it is okay to reach out and ask for help. in unity, join women in this fight and become an ally. it starts with you, your actions, and your behaviors. always be conscious of them. change the script and language you use. realize the implications. be present. listen intently. keep growing. please keep fighting. thank you.

#ngocswny #16daysofactivism #hearmetoo #orangetheworld #endvaw #metoo #believesurvivors #wewillnotbesilenced #timesup #standup #consentissexy #consentculture #sexworkiswork #notaskingforit

text:
this is not consent. 
as part of my senior show, the unspoken: voices of the voiceless, i did a performance piece regarding sexual assault. clothing is never an indication of consent to having sex. this is a social critique of victim blaming and the declaration that rape is justifiable dependent on the clothing worn during the assault.  no matter what an individual wears, they should never be subjected to rape, nor should they feel obligated to have sex.

in ireland, a 17 year old girl had her underwear used in a rape case with cousel saying "you have to look at the way she was dressed. she was wearing a thong with a lace front." during this performance, i wore underwear that matched this description. 
this needs to stop. 
#thisisnotconsent #dontfuckingtouchme #metoo #timesup #sexualassaultsurvivor #sexualassault

text:
this is how russians travel from earth to saturn !!! through dimensional portals... in 2015 nasa researchers disclosed the truth about time travel and dimensional portals. there are places all over the universe we can travel to in an instant, using energetic portals in space, and the use of our consciousness.
the proof is indeed mounting that there are portals to other worlds. though the documentation is still ‘sketchy’! apparently, tesla too was obsessed with time travel. he worked on a time machine and reportedly succeeded, saying: ‘i could see the past, present and future all at the same time.’ tesla’s time travel experiment: i could see the past, present and future all at the same time’

what happened to tesla’s files from there, as well as what exactly was in those files, remains shrouded in mystery—and ripe for conspiracy theories. the fbi has finally declassified its files on nikola tesla, but questions remain.

text:
trauma bonding is a chemical bond created by the intermittent release of stress hormones and pleasure hormones, caused by the abuser running hot and cold or flipping between dr. jekyll and mr. hyde.

the switch between dealing with the nice guy and then the bad guy  confuses your adrenals and creates a rollercoaster of emotions which is quite literally facilitated by the chemicals in your body.

this creates a chemical bond, by the means of which can only be broken by going no contact from the abuser.

text: does this tervis tumbler offend you? i hope not. apparently, a few radio stations have pulled this classic christmas song from their holiday rotation because it sounds “rapey” (is that even a word?). what are we turning into as a nation when we concern ourselves with a fluff pop  song written in 1944 while there are many more pressing issues we’re facing? i understand the #metoo movement, and i support what they are trying to accomplish, but this is ridiculously overreaching and might prove harmful to their message if they want to be taken seriously. all the lady agrees to at the end of the song is another drink. but so what? have you heard some of the crap that’s on the radio these days? why is it easier to pick on an old song? instead of banning it outright, one radio station conducted a poll asking their listeners if they should remove the tune. 91% said to keep playing it. last time i checked, we live in a democracy where majority rules, so there you go. in the meantime, i’m going to toast to the holiday season with my tervis tumbler filled with hot chocolate, and i’ll ask my wife if she’d like some too, because baby, it’s cold outside.

text:
what is consent?
consent is an agreement between participants to engage in sexual activity. there are many ways to give consent, and some of those are discussed below. consent doesn’t have to be verbal, but verbally agreeing to different sexual activities can help both you and your partner respect each other’s boundaries.

how does consent work in real life?
when you’re engaging in sexual activity, consent is about communication. and it should happen every time. giving consent for one activity, one time, does not mean giving consent for increased or recurring sexual contact. for example, agreeing to kiss someone doesn’t give that person permission to remove your clothes. having sex with someone in the past doesn’t give that person permission to have sex with you again in the future.

you can change your mind at any time.
you can withdraw consent at any point if you feel uncomfortable. it’s important to clearly communicate to your partner that you are no longer comfortable with this activity and wish to stop. the best way to ensure both parties are comfortable with any sexual activity is to talk about it.

positive consent can look like this:
- communicating when you change the type or degree of sexual activity with phrases like “is this ok?”
- explicitly agreeing to certain activities, either by saying “yes” or another affirmative statement, like “i’m open to trying.”
- using physical cues to let the other person know you’re comfortable taking things to the next level
it does not look like this:
- refusing to acknowledge “no”
- assuming that wearing certain clothes, flirting, or kissing is an invitation for anything more
- someone being under the legal age of consent, as defined by the state
- someone being incapacitated because of drugs or alcohol
- pressuring someone into sexual activity by using fear or intimidation
- assuming you have permission to engage in a sexual act because you’ve done it in the past (content for this post was found on the rape abuse and incest national network (rainn) website.)

text_retweet:
#repost @peter_svensson_ (@get_repost)
・・・
hej @svt . i inledning av ert sändningstillstånd finner jag formuleringen; ”verksamheten ska präglas av oberoende och stark integritet och bedrivas självständigt i förhållande till såväl staten som olika ekonomiska, politiska och andra intressen och maktsfärer i samhället.” ni har i alla tider varit en normerande kraft. ni har gett oss perspektiven vi många gånger saknat. delat stora som små berättelser från världens alla hörn. avslöjat orättvisor och missförhållanden lokalt likväl som globalt. ni har gett annorlunda människor plats, främjat olikheter, gjort oss mer toleranta och accepterande mer nyfikna och öppna. ni har lyft minoriteters kamp och allas lika rättigheter. ni har lärt oss räkna, läsa och förstå. för det är jag tacksam men precis som fredrik backman skriver i björnstad så är ju kultur både ”allt vi uppmuntrar och allt vi tillåter” och här börjar det skava för mig. 
under och efter vittnesmålen i #metoo börjar jag mer och mer förstå att ni samtidigt som ni gett oss allt vi har att vara tacksamma för också varit mer eller mindre avgörande för den sortens kultur som möjliggjort att normerande män med makt i decennier kunnat begå övergrepp och sexuellt våld mot kvinnor. ni har både indirekt och direkt gett män makt och möjlighet att bete sig illa för det har aldrig funnits några vägledande konsekvenser. ni har snarare tvärtom varit oerhört toleranta, förlängt kontrakt, höjt löner, tilldelat huvudroller och programledaruppdrag år ut och år in. trots att ni många gånger vetat om deras gränsöverskridande beteenden både i jobbet och privat. ni har under årtionden varit helt avgörande för att skitbeteenden och övergrepp har kunnat pågått. så här ett år efter #metoo så blir jag därför förvånad när ni väljer en man att ringa in nyåret som för så många av oss förkroppsligar #metoo och den kultur som vi nu vill lämna bakom oss. jag undrar om ni anser att ni hedrar ert uppdrag med det valet. jag undrar om ni anser att det här är ert sätt att visa att ni tar vittnesmålen under #metoo på allvar? integritet? jag undrar en massa mer saker men kanske att ni kan förklara det närmast obegripliga till att börja med? tacksam fö

text:
#metoo #domesticviolence messiah @louisfarrakhan teaches "there are things in our lives that have been done to us. from the time we were babies, a word from a mother that wasn't thinking; a father that didn't care; a teacher that was off the mark who, when they said things, whose words became “commands” to you. 
and these commands are in your head, stored in the subconscious mind. 
any woman who has been ‪molested‬, who has been ‪raped‬ by a father, by an uncle, by a friend, by a relative: college doesn't free you; church doesn't free you from that pain. it gives you an emotional escape. but to relieve you, and give you a chance to live … see, the scientologists call this process ‪auditing ‬. but we who are muslims, we who are scriptural people, we don't use the term engrams. in theology, we call it the exorcising of demons.

and so, when you're being audited, they just ask you to go back. 
every one of us has a file in our head, and the auditor will take you back to a moment of pain  which is something that people did to you, not so much what you did to others.

when you look at our behavior, you're looking at “demons” that are sitting up inside of us that have to come out in order for us to be what god intends for us to be. 
and that means that every one of us have to be purified! 
all of us!"@louisfarrakhan: preparation of the mind

text:
transformation ~ when you start to take care of you - really take care of you, you begin to see the changes.  it doesn’t happen overnight and it does take time. 
although i initially hesitated for a second or two, i knew signing up to work with my coach was what i needed.  i wouldn’t be where i’m at if i hadn’t. have you asked yourself what it is that you really need? 
if you are tired of your life as it is and want to make a change, then this might be your time for your transformation.  it is never too late to improve our lives, be happy with our choices and ourselves, and be on the path to making our goals and dreams actually real.  we can want it all we want, but until we begin the work to get there, it’s only a dream.  let’s make it our reality. 
what is it that you want your life to look like?  click on the link in my bio ➡️ @denisestyer to schedule a call with me.  we can discuss what it is you are looking for and how we might work together to make it happen. the great thing is you can live anywhere for us to work together as long as you have internet. i love working with women and watching the transformation unfold! 🐛🦋💜
